If the transition matrix is

\begin{align*}
P=\begin{bmatrix}
8/10  &  3/10  &  1/10\\
2/10  &  3/10  &  7/10\\
0  &  4/10  &  2/10
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

then the operation P\textbf{x}=\textbf{b} gives us the probability of
being in each of the three states \textbf{b} based on where we started,
\textbf{x}. We are told that we are equally likely to be in any of the
three states so we have as our vector,

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}=\left[1/3,1/3,1/3\right].
\end{align*}

To find out the probabilities of being in each state after one
transition we compute P\textbf{x},

\begin{align*}
P\mathbf{x}=\begin{bmatrix}
8/10  &  3/10  &  1/10\\
2/10  &  3/10  &  7/10\\
0  &  4/10  &  2/10
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1/3\\
1/3\\
1/3
\end{bmatrix}
=\begin{bmatrix}
2/5\\
2/5\\
1/5
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

Therefore we get that \textbf{the probability of being in state 3 is
1/5}. Notice that the output probabilities sum to 1. This is a
requirement since we only allow transitions from states 1 to 3, this
summation to 1 simply says that no matter where we start we will end up
somewhere in states 1 to 3.
